Apart from the parts which are always present (editor, menu, toolbar), the Process Designer workbench also consists of variable elements called views. These views can be opened, closed and moved independently, allowing a user to customize the workbench structure. A view can be opened using the menu entry with the views name in the *View* category. To close a view simply click on the cross on the right side of the view header. A view can be moved to a different position on the workbench via drag and drop of the view header. Light gray lines indicate the new position of the view while dragging. Views can be stacked by moving two or more to the same position. When dragging a view onto another, a green line next to the header of the target view indicates if it will be placed left or right of it. Switch between stacked views by clicking on a header.

There are two different workbench configurations called *Edit* and *Test*, each with its own layout and combination of views. These configurations are called perspectives. Switch between them by clicking the *Edit* or *Test* button on the right side of the toolbar. Changes to the workbench done in one of those perspectives will only affect this one and will be remembered when switching to the other. By default, *Edit* includes only the views required for editing the process and *Test* includes views for executing processes. Both can be modified for different purposes.

## Outline
The *Outline* view displays a tree representation containing all parts of the process currently open in the editor. The different nodes of the tree are listed and explained below. The context menu for an entry can be opened by right clicking on the node.

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 4. Outline View*

### Namespaces
![](data:image/png;base64,)

This node in the outline tree can be used to edit the namespaces of the process. The *Add *entry in the context menu of the node opens a dialog for adding a new namespace. Enter a prefix and namespace into the corresponding fields and click *OK* to create it. The *Edit* entry in the context menu of a namespace opens a dialog where you can modify the namespace and its prefix. The *Delete* entry in the context menu of a namspace deletes this namespace.

### Credentials Registry
![](data:image/png;base64,)

This node and its children in the outline tree can be used to manage the credentials registry of the process definition file. Add credentials descriptors to the registry by selecting the *Add *entry in the context menu of the CredentialsRegistry node. Descriptors can be edited or deleted using the *Edit* and *Delete* entries in its context menu. Adding or editing a descriptor opens a dialog. The text fields in the upper part of the dialog define the URI(s) for which the credentials should be used. Fields can be left empty, the credentials will be applied to any URI which fits the parts which were provided. If the *Preemptive* flag is checked, the credentials will always be provided by default, otherwise the first request is sent without credentials to find out whether the server requests them. Below the *Preemptive* checkbox, the credentials can be defined. The authentication type must be selected from the dropdown. Additional fields (if applicable) are shown below, depending on the selected type. Click *OK* to apply the information.

### Credentials Configs
![](data:image/png;base64,)

This node represents the credentials config registry of the process definition. The config registry can contain one credentials config for each supported authentication type. the registry can be modified by double clicking on the node or selecting the *Edit* entry in the context menu. This will open a dialog showing the supported authentication types on the left. When a type is selected and it doesnt have a credentials config yet, there is an *Add *button on the right, which can be used to create a config. When there is a config for the authentication type, the *Add* button changes to a *Delete* button and the fields specific to this type are shown below.

### Constants
![](data:image/png;base64,)

This node in the outline tree can be used to edit the process constants. The *Add* entry in the context menu of the node opens a dialog for adding a new constant. Enter a name and select a type for the constant. Add values with the *Add*, remove them with the *Remove* button. Check the *public* checkbox to make the constant public. Check the *transitive* checkbox to make the constant transitive. Modify the value by clicking on the list entry. Click *OK* to create the constant. The *Edit* entry in the context menu of a constant opens the same dialog as for adding a constant, where it can be modified. The *Delete* entry in the context menu of a constant deletes this constant.

### Elements
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Contains a list of all process elements in the process in the same order they occur in the XML representation. Selecting an element in the outline will also select it in the editor and vice versa. Process elements in this list can be copied, cut and pasted via context menu or shortcut. The *Edit* entry in the context menu of a process element opens a dialog where you can modify the name of the element. The *Delete* entry in the context menu of a process element deletes it from the process. With the *Move Up* and *Move Down* entries in the context menu, the position of a process element within the list can be changed. This also changes the order in the persisted XML representation.

Process elements which can contain mappings have either a child *Mappings* or two children *Inputs* and *Outputs*, depending on what is applicable. These nodes contain a list of nodes representing the mappings belonging to the element. Mappings can be copied from here via context menu or shortcut. Each mapping node again has two children *Sources* and *Targets*. *Sources* contains the list of mapping sources, *Targets* contains the list of variable targets.

### Connections
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Contains a list of all connections in the process in the same order they occur in the XML representation. Selecting a connection in the outline will also select it in the editor and vice versa. The *Delete* entry in the context menu of a connection deletes it from the process. With the *Move Up* and *Move Down* entries in the context menu, the position of a connection within the list can be changed. This also changes the order in the XML representation.

### Notes
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Contains a list of all notes in the process diagram. The *Edit* entry in the context menu of a note in this list opens a dialog where the text of the note can be modified. The *Delete* entry in the context menu of a note deletes this note.

## Overview![](data:image/png;base64,)
The *Overview* provides a smaller image of the complete process diagram. If the process diagram is larger than the visible part of the editor, the blue box in the overview can be moved using the mouse to move the visible part in the editor.

## Properties
![](data:image/png;base64,)

The *Properties* view displays different types of properties for the currently selected element in the active editor or view. For each property type there is a separate tab which is only visible if the type is applicable for the selected element. For more information about the individual property types see section [Properties](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-properties).

## Resource Explorer
![](data:image/png;base64,)

The *Resource Explorer* view contains an embedded Resource Explorer. It is possible to open processes directly from this view by navigating to the IPD file and double clicking it. For further information regarding the Resource Explorer please consult the Resource Explorer documentation.

## Validation
![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 5. Validation View*

The *Validation* view shows a list of potential problems which can lead to errors when executing the process in the currently active editor. Each problem has a message, a level of severity and a source. The *Message* column provides a description for the problem. The *Severity* column indicates how critical a problem is for process execution. The severity levels are explained below:

**WARNING**

The issue might cause failures or unwanted behaviour but does not prevent execution.

**ERROR**

Execution of the process will certainly cause problems, therefore the process will not be instantiated by Processs Engine.

**FATAL**

The process definition is invalid and cannot be loaded properly. Process Designer will prevent saving a process with such a problem because information might be lost.

## Process Execution List
![](data:image/png;base64,)

The *Process Execution List* view lists process executions in a table.

The first table column shows an icon which indicates whether the execution is connected or disconnected. An execution is disconnected if the connection to the executing Process Engine has been lost at some point before the process has ended and Process Designer cannot receive any automatic updates on the status of the process instance any more. As long as it is possible to receive updates for a running execution, a process is shown as connected. A user can attempt to reconnect a disconnected execution using the *Reconnect *button in the toolbar.

Other columns of the table:

Start Time

Shows a timestamp for the moment, the process has been started.

Process

Displays the URI or name of the executed process file.

Launch Config

Shows the name of the used launch configuration if the process was started from Process Designer.

Engine

Shows the name of the Process Engine configuration used for execution.

Status

Displays the current process execution state for this execution provided by the Process Engine.

When a process is executed from Process Designer, an entry is automatically added to the list. Executions which have not been started from Process Designer or already removed from the list, can also be added using the *Add Execution* button in the toolbar. The button opens a dialog which shows available process instances for configured Process Engines. In the combo box at the top an engine configuration can be selected. By default the config currently set in the toolbar is selected. If the *Show all* checkbox is selected, instances which are already represented by an execution in the *Process Execution List* are shown with a grey background. Otherwise they are hidden. Select one or more instances from the table and click *OK* to add them. Doubleclicking on an instance will directly add it and close the dialog. Instead of selecting from the table, one or more execution IDs can also put into the *Execution IDs* text field at the bottom manually. If instances for these execution IDs exist for the selected Process Engine, they will be added when *OK* is pressed. Otherwise an error message is shown.

#### Toolbar
- *Add Execution*: Opens the dialog for adding process executions.

- *Remove*: Removes the currently selected process execution from the list. This only removes it from the list maintained by Process Designer, not from the list of executions maintained Process Engine. If the execution which should be removed is still running, the user will be prompted whether or not the execution should be terminated before removing it.

- *Remove All*: Removes all process executions from the list. If one or more of the executions are still running, the user will be prompted whether or not they should be terminated before removing them.

- *Terminate*/*Kill*: Terminates the selected execution if it is not finished yet. A terminated process which has not returned yet can be killed with the same button.

- *Refresh*: Refreshes the status of the selected execution.

- *Reconnect*: Reconnect an execution which has been disconnected. If succesfull, the reconnected execution can receive automatic updates from the Process Engine again.

## Pipeline View
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Displays the variables in the pipeline of the process execution, which is selected in the *Process Execution List* view. Is empty if no execution is selected. The variables of the pipeline are listed in the table which fills most of the view. For a finished process this only shows the variables which were mapped in the end element. The *Name* column contains the name of the variable as it was defined in the variable target when mapping it. The *Type* column shows the type of the variable value. The *Value* column contains the value(s) of a variable. In case of multiple values for one variable, the values are separated by a semicolon. For displaying the values separately, a variable with multiple values can be uncollapsed using the arrow symbol at the beginning of the line. When selecting a variable in the table, the field below the table displays the value(s) of the variable. For larger values which do not fit into one line, the size of the field can be increased by dragging the border between the table and the field upwards.

## Log
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Displays the process state log, trace log and diagnostic log of a process execution selected in the *Process Execution List* view. The log messages are displayed as text lines in chronological order from top to bottom.

Process Designer can only receive log messages via message logging. For this it is necessary to have a message logger configured in Process Engine and for Process Designer to use it. How to activate message logging in Process Designer is described in chapter [Process Engine](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-preferences#process-engine). For more information about logging please consult the Process Engine documentation. The *Clear Log* button in the right upper corner of the view deletes all log messages for the selected process execution.

## Help
![](data:image/png;base64,)

For activities and tasks selected in the editor or the palette, this view shows documentation, including the expected input and output parameters. It is only available if the currently selected Process Engine provides the documentation for the selected activity/task.
